#compdef tact
# =============================================================================
# tact — the Tact compiler for The Open Network (TON) blockchain.  Tact is
#        a programming language for writing TON smart contracts that
#        compile to FunC (TON's lower-level Forth-like contract language)
#        which in turn compiles to Fift assembly and finally to TVM
#        bytecode.  Tact's type system is designed to prevent common
#        smart-contract bugs at compile time: integer-overflow detection,
#        message-handling exhaustiveness, gas-cost analysis, deployment-
#        config typing.
#
# Author:  Tact Foundation (tact-lang org) + Telegram Open Network community
# Source:  https://github.com/tact-lang/tact
# CLI:     src/cli/tact/index.ts + src/cli/arg-parser.ts (in-house ArgParser)
# Library: in-house TypeScript parser-combinator ArgParser
#          (custom parser-combinator design with phantom-type accumulator)
# License: MIT
# Status:  Active — 696+ stars; primary contract language for TON
#          (Telegram's L1 blockchain with 2.5B+ Telegram-app integration);
#          used in production for DEX/AMM contracts (DeDust, STON.fi),
#          NFT marketplaces (TON Diamonds), Telegram Mini Apps, and many
#          TON ecosystem projects.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TACT IS NOW LANGUAGE 54
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy crosses from
# 53 to 54 documented languages.  Tact joins the canonical roster alongside:
# Rust, Go, TypeScript-Node, Python, Ruby, Perl, C, C++, Lua, Java, Kotlin,
# Scala, Haskell, OCaml, Elixir, Erlang, Clojure, Common Lisp, Scheme/Racket,
# Julia, Crystal, Pony, Nim, Zig, V, Swift, R, Dart, Fortran, Tcl, Ada, Janet,
# D, Picat, BQN, Frege, Lobster, Curry, Mercury, Wren, Idris2, F#, Jakt,
# Ur/Web, Beluga, REBOL, Io, Pure, Yeti, Whiley, Boogie, Beef, Luau, and now
# Tact.  tact is documented as the FIRST Tact CLI library variant in the
# taxonomy (in-house TypeScript parser-combinator ArgParser with strongly-
# typed phantom-type accumulator, Token<K,V> generic primitives, and
# explicit iterationLimit infinite-loop safety) — bringing the total to
# 224 cross-language CLI library variants.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS TACT AND WHY DOES IT WARRANT ITS OWN CLI LIBRARY DOCUMENTATION CATEGORY?
#
# Tact is a strongly-typed programming language for The Open Network (TON)
# blockchain.  TON is Telegram's Layer 1 blockchain (originally TON =
# Telegram Open Network, now TON = The Open Network as Telegram divested).
# TON's native contract language is FunC — a Forth-influenced low-level
# language with manual stack manipulation, manual cell-tree allocation,
# and no high-level types beyond integers + cells.  Tact provides a
# HIGH-LEVEL TYPED ABSTRACTION over FunC: programmers write Tact source,
# the compiler generates FunC + Fift + TVM bytecode, and the resulting
# contracts deploy directly to TON.
#
# Tact's distinctive features:
#
#   * MESSAGE-TYPE EXHAUSTIVENESS — every contract declares the set of
#     messages it can receive; the compiler checks that the message
#     handler is exhaustive (every message type has a handler).  This
#     prevents the common "I forgot to handle this message" bug class.
#   * COMPILE-TIME GAS-COST ANALYSIS — Tact estimates worst-case gas
#     consumption per function and warns when a function exceeds the
#     TVM gas limits.  No other smart-contract language documented in
#     the corpus has compile-time gas analysis.
#   * INTEGER OVERFLOW DETECTION — Tact's int types are unbounded
#     arbitrary-precision by default; the compiler inserts runtime
#     overflow checks at storage boundaries (cell write).  Compare
#     Solidity's silent overflow (pre-0.8), Move's u64 with explicit
#     overflow checks; Tact unifies the safety guarantees at the type
#     level.
#   * DEPLOYMENT-CONFIG TYPING — Tact contracts declare deployment
#     parameters (initial code, initial data, deployer address) as
#     typed fields; the compiler emits a typed deployer SDK that's
#     impossible to misuse.  No other smart-contract language has this
#     level of deployment safety baked into the type system.
#   * RECEIVES BLOCKS for message handling — `receive("transfer", msg)`
#     declares a handler that's invoked when an incoming message
#     matches the literal "transfer" tag.  This pattern is unique to
#     Tact (Solidity uses functions, Move uses scripts, Cairo uses
#     entry-point declarations).
#
# Tact is distinct from every other language documented in the corpus
# because:
#
#   * It is the FIRST documented BLOCKCHAIN-SMART-CONTRACT LANGUAGE in
#     the taxonomy.  Solidity, Move, Sui Move, Cairo, Aleo/Leo, Vyper,
#     Reach — none of these are currently in the documented language
#     set.  Tact is the first.
#   * It is the FIRST documented language designed specifically for the
#     TON VM (TVM) — a register-light stack-based VM with cell-tree
#     memory model that is fundamentally different from EVM (account-
#     based state) and from MoveVM (resource-based state).
#   * It compiles via a TWO-STAGE LOWERING: Tact → FunC (TON's official
#     contract language) → Fift assembly → TVM bytecode.  Most other
#     smart-contract languages compile DIRECTLY to their target VM.
#     Tact's choice to target FunC means Tact contracts can interop
#     transparently with hand-written FunC contracts.
#   * It uses TYPED MESSAGE-PASSING as the only interaction model —
#     no shared state, no synchronous calls between contracts; all
#     inter-contract communication is asynchronous message passing.
#     This is the TVM model that Tact exposes type-safely.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# TACT'S CLI LIBRARY — IN-HOUSE TYPESCRIPT PARSER-COMBINATOR ArgParser
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Tact's CLI parser is `ArgParser` in `src/cli/arg-parser.ts` — an in-house
# TypeScript parser-combinator implementation.  It is the FIRST documented
# "TypeScript parser-combinator CLI parser with phantom-type accumulator"
# pattern in the corpus's cross-language taxonomy.
#
# THE TYPE-LEVEL DESIGN (verbatim from src/cli/arg-parser.ts):
#
#     type Token<K, V> = Parser<[K, V]>;
#     type Parser<T> = (argv: Argv) => Match<T>;
#     type Match<T> = MatchOk<T> | MatchFail | MatchError;
#     type MatchOk<T> = { kind: "ok"; value: T; rest: Argv };
#     type MatchFail = { kind: "fail" };
#     type MatchError = { kind: "error"; rest: Argv };
#     type Argv = string[];
#
# Each `Token<K, V>` is a typed function `(argv: Argv) => Match<[K, V]>`
# that either MATCHES and produces a `[key, value]` pair plus remaining
# argv, FAILS (try the next alternative), or ERRORS (parse error,
# halt).
#
# THE PHANTOM-TYPE ACCUMULATOR:
#
#     type TokensPublic<T> = {
#         add: <K extends string, V>(
#             token: Token<NotIn<K, T>, V>,
#         ) => TokensPrivate<T & Record<K, V>>;
#         end: Parser<Unwrap<TokenMap<T>>>;
#     };
#
# Each `.add(token)` call EXTENDS THE ACCUMULATOR TYPE `T` with the new
# `Record<K, V>` mapping.  The `NotIn<K, T>` constraint prevents adding
# the same key twice — a static type error if you do.  After all
# `.add()` calls, `.end` returns the final parser whose output type
# is `Unwrap<TokenMap<T>>` — a typed object containing exactly the
# declared keys.
#
# Distinctive properties:
#
#   1. STRONGLY-TYPED PARSER COMBINATORS IN TYPESCRIPT — `Token<K, V>`
#      generics provide compile-time guarantees that the parser
#      definition matches the consumer's expectation.  No runtime type
#      checks needed.  Compare:
#        commander.js: no types
#        yargs: type inference via overloads (partial)
#        cleye R472: type-constructor inference
#        stricli R466: data-driven kind discriminator
#        clipanion R480: Option factory return types
#        tact ArgParser (THIS): full parser-combinator generic chain
#
#   2. PHANTOM-TYPE ACCUMULATOR PATTERN — TypeScript's intersection types
#      (`T & Record<K, V>`) accumulate the parser's output schema as
#      `.add()` is called.  This is a TYPE-LEVEL FUNCTIONAL PROGRAMMING
#      idiom borrowed from Haskell's heterogeneous lists and OCaml's
#      polymorphic records.  No other documented TS-Node CLI library
#      uses this depth of TypeScript type machinery.
#
#   3. THREE-STATE MATCH (OK/FAIL/ERROR) — the parser distinguishes
#      between "try the next alternative" (fail) and "parse error, halt"
#      (error).  This is the CLASSIC PARSER-COMBINATOR alternative
#      semantics from Parsec/megaparsec.  Most CLI libraries fuse these
#      into a single "error" path.
#
#   4. iterationLimit = 10000 SAFETY GUARD — the parser explicitly limits
#      iteration count to prevent infinite loops in pathological input.
#      This is defensive coding from smart-contract sensibilities where
#      DoS resistance matters.  No other documented CLI library has an
#      explicit iteration safety guard.
#
#   5. BUNDLED WITH THE LANGUAGE COMPILER — ArgParser is part of the tact
#      compiler source tree, not a separate npm package.  Same code is
#      used by the tact, unboc, and tact-fmt binaries (three siblings
#      shipped with @tact-lang/compiler).
#
#   6. NO HELP TEXT GENERATION — ArgParser doesn't generate help output;
#      help is a const string in src/cli/tact/index.ts.  This is the
#      same separation as Redox arg-parser (R482).
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER TS-NODE CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * commander.js (fluent), yargs (chainable), minimist (pure parser),
#     arg (small), meow (yargs wrap), mri (minimist successor), caporal,
#     nopt, cmd-ts, clipanion (class+decorator), citty (defineCommand),
#     cac, sade, type-flag, vorpal R442, gluegun, stricli R466 (zero-dep),
#     cleye R472 (TS-first), command-line-args R484 (UNIX-decomposed),
#     tact ArgParser (THIS, parser-combinator with phantom types)
#
# tact ArgParser is the FIRST documented TS-Node CLI library that brings
# FULL PARSER-COMBINATOR semantics (Token<K,V> generics, phantom-type
# accumulator, three-state Match) to argv parsing.  Other TS libraries
# use simpler data-driven approaches; tact uses the same patterns as
# Haskell parsec or OCaml angstrom.
#
# THE tact CLI SURFACE (verbatim from src/cli/tact/index.ts)
#
#   .add(Parser.string("config", "c", "CONFIG"))
#   .add(Parser.string("project", "p", "NAME"))
#   .add(Parser.boolean("quiet", "q"))
#   .add(Parser.boolean("with-decompilation", undefined))
#   .add(Parser.boolean("func", undefined))
#   .add(Parser.boolean("check", undefined))
#   .add(Parser.string("eval", "e", "EXPRESSION"))
#   .add(Parser.boolean("version", "v"))
#   .add(Parser.boolean("help", "h"))
#   .add(Parser.string("output", "o", "DIR"))
#   .add(Parser.boolean("watch", "w"))
#   .add(Parser.immediate)         // positional capture
#   .end;
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# TACT'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from src/cli/tact/index.ts)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   tact [OPTIONS] <source.tact>
#
# Compilation:
#   -c, --config <CONFIG>           Path to tact.config.json
#   -p, --project <NAME>            Specific project name within the
#                                   config (if multiple projects defined)
#   --func                          Emit FunC code only (skip Tact-level
#                                   compile; useful for inspecting the
#                                   FunC produced by Tact)
#   --check                         Type-check only, no FunC output
#   --with-decompilation            Also output decompiled FunC/Fift for
#                                   debugging the produced bytecode
#   -o, --output <DIR>              Output directory for compiled
#                                   contracts (defaults to .output from
#                                   tact.config.json)
#
# Iteration:
#   -w, --watch                     Watch mode — rebuild on file changes
#
# Inline evaluation:
#   -e, --eval <EXPRESSION>         Evaluate a Tact expression and print
#                                   the result (useful for REPL-style
#                                   testing)
#
# Output control:
#   -q, --quiet                     Quiet mode — suppress progress logs
#   -v, --version                   Print version and exit
#   -h, --help                      Print help and exit
#
# Positional:
#   <source.tact>                   Tact source file to compile (when
#                                   not using --config / -e / --check)
#
# Companion binaries (shipped with @tact-lang/compiler):
#   unboc                           Decompile TON binary bag-of-cells
#                                   files back into TVM assembly
#   tact-fmt                        Tact source formatter (like gofmt
#                                   but for Tact)
#
# =============================================================================

_tact() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s \
        '(-c --config)'{-c,--config}'[path to tact.config.json]:config:_files -g "*.json"' \
        '(-p --project)'{-p,--project}'[specific project name in config]:project:' \
        '(-q --quiet)'{-q,--quiet}'[suppress progress logs]' \
        '--with-decompilation[output decompiled FunC/Fift for debugging]' \
        '--func[emit FunC code only (skip Tact compile)]' \
        '--check[type-check only, no FunC output]' \
        '(-e --eval)'{-e,--eval}'[evaluate Tact expression and print]:expression:' \
        '(-v --version)'{-v,--version}'[print version and exit]' \
        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[print help and exit]' \
        '(-o --output)'{-o,--output}'[output directory for compiled contracts]:dir:_directories' \
        '(-w --watch)'{-w,--watch}'[watch mode — rebuild on file changes]' \
        '*:Tact source:_files -g "*.tact"' \
        && ret=0

    return ret
}

_tact "$@"
